<p><strong>Explanation</strong></p>
<p>The traditional definition of a <em>DriverEntry</em> function is as foll=
ows:</p>
<div><div id=3D"highlighter_721206" class=3D"syntaxhighlighter  c"><table b=
order=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"gut=
ter"><div class=3D"line number1 index0 alt2">1</div><div class=3D"line numb=
er2 index1 alt1">2</div><div class=3D"line number3 index2 alt2">3</div><div=
 class=3D"line number4 index3 alt1">4</div></td><td class=3D"code"><div cla=
ss=3D"container"><div class=3D"line number1 index0 alt2"><code class=3D"c p=
lain">NTSTATUS DriverEntry(</code></div><div class=3D"line number2 index1 a=
lt1"><code class=3D"c spaces">&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><code class=3D"c plain">_I=
n_&nbsp; </code><code class=3D"c keyword bold">struct</code> <code class=3D=
"c plain">_DRIVER_OBJECT *DriverObject,</code></div><div class=3D"line numb=
er3 index2 alt2"><code class=3D"c spaces">&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><code class=3D=
"c plain">_In_&nbsp; PUNICODE_STRING RegistryPath</code></div><div class=3D=
"line number4 index3 alt1"><code class=3D"c plain">)</code></div></div></td=
></tr></tbody></table></div></div>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Under normal circumstances, the second pa=
rameter contains a valid pointer into a string describing the driver=E2=80=
=99s registry path. For <em>diskdump.sys</em>, however, the semantics of th=
e parameter are different; the kernel seems to use it as some kind of a sha=
red structure, both read from and written to by diskdump.sys. In fact, one =
of the first operations executed by the routine is the following call:</p>
<div><div id=3D"highlighter_34193" class=3D"syntaxhighlighter  c"><table bo=
rder=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"gutt=
er"><div class=3D"line number1 index0 alt2">1</div></td><td class=3D"code">=
<div class=3D"container"><div class=3D"line number1 index0 alt2"><code clas=
s=3D"c functions bold">memset</code><code class=3D"c plain">(*(</code><code=
 class=3D"c keyword bold">void</code> <code class=3D"c plain">**)(RegistryP=
ath + 8), 0, 0x10000u);</code></div></div></td></tr></tbody></table></div><=
/div>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">That=E2=80=99s right =E2=80=93 the driver=
 ends up zeroing-out 65,536 bytes of the kernel pool area. After that happe=
ns, it doesn=E2=80=99t take more than a few seconds (usually far less) to s=
ee the screen being filled with blue pixels. Very difficult in reliable exp=
loitation, but perhaps possible with the right degree of kernel pool massag=
ing.</p>
